definition.value: The continuation of translation beyond a stop codon by the use of a special tRNA that recognizes the UAG and UGA codons as modified amino acids, rather than as termination codons.

label.value: positive regulation of NF-kappaB transcription factor activity by ER overload response

definition.value: The conversion of inactive NF-kappaB to the active form, thereby allowing it to activate transcription of target genes, as a result of signaling from the endoplasmic reticulum.

label.value: positive regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter involved in unfolded protein response

definition.value: The activation of genes whose promoters contain a specific sequence elements such as the unfolded protein response element (UPRE -  consensus CAGCGTG) or the ER stress-response element (ERSE -  CCAAN(N)9CCACG), as a result of signaling via the unfolded protein response.

label.value: negative regulation of transcription during mitosis

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of transcription during mitosis.

label.value: negative regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase I promoter during mitosis

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase I promoter during mitosis.

label.value: negative regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter during mitosis

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter during mitosis.

label.value: negative regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase III promoter during mitosis

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase III promoter during mitosis.

label.value: positive regulation of transcription on exit from mitosis

definition.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of transcription as the cell leaves M phase. M phase is the part of the mitotic cell cycle during which mitosis and cytokinesis take place.

label.value: positive regulation of transcription on exit from mitosis, from RNA polymerase I promoter

definition.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase I promoter as the cell leaves M phase. M phase is the part of the mitotic cell cycle during which mitosis and cytokinesis take place.

label.value: positive regulation of transcription on exit from mitosis, from RNA polymerase II promoter

definition.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter as the cell leaves M phase. M phase is the part of the mitotic cell cycle during which mitosis and cytokinesis take place.

label.value: positive regulation of transcription on exit from mitosis, from RNA polymerase III promoter

definition.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase III promoter as the cell leaves M phase. M phase is the part of the mitotic cell cycle during which mitosis and cytokinesis take place.

label.value: positive regulation of transcription of Notch receptor target

definition.value: The activation of transcription of specific genes as a result of Notch signaling, mediated by the Notch intracellular domain.

label.value: positive regulation of hh target transcription factor activity

definition.value: Any process that increases the activity of a transcription factor that activates transcription of Hedgehog-target genes in response to Smoothened signaling. In Drosophila, Cubitus interruptus (Ci) is the only identified transcription factor so far in the Hedgehog signaling pathway. In vertebrates, members of the Gli protein family are activated in this way. Activation of the Gli|Ci transcription factor is distinct from its stabilization, when proteolytic cleavage is inhibited.

label.value: negative regulation of oskar mRNA translation

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate that oskar mRNAs are effectively translated into protein.

label.value: positive regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter by pheromones

definition.value: Any process involving pheromones that activates or increases the rate of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter.

label.value: positive regulation of central gap gene transcription

definition.value: The activation of genes encoding transcription factors in the central region of an insect embryo by a combination of maternal regulatory signals and interactions among themselves -  exemplified by the activation of expression of the Drosophila Kruppel gene by the hunchback and bicoid gene products.

label.value: positive regulation of posterior gap gene transcription

definition.value: The activation of genes encoding transcription factors in the posterior region of an insect embryo by a combination of maternal regulatory signals and interactions among themselves -  exemplified by the activation of expression of the Drosophila knirps gene.

label.value: positive regulation of terminal gap gene transcription

definition.value: The activation of genes encoding transcription factors at the anterior and posterior ends of an insect embryo by a combination of maternal regulatory signals and interactions among themselves -  exemplified by the activation of expression of the Drosophila tailless and huckebein genes.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of rhodopsin gene expression. This includes transcriptional, translational, or posttranslational regulation.

label.value: regulation of mating-type specific transcription, DNA-templated

definition.value: Any mating-type specific process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cellular DNA-templated transcription.
Compensating for the two-fold variation in X - autosome chromosome ratios between sexes by a global activation or inactivation of all, or most of, genes on one or both of the X chromosomes.
The electron-lucent layer of the basal lamina adjacent to the basal plasma membrane of the cells that rest on the lamina.
The electron-dense layer of the basal lamina -  lies just below the lamina lucida.
A layer of the basal lamina that contains collagen fibrils and connects the basal lamina to the underlying connective tissue.

The function of a family of small chemotactic cytokines -  their name is derived from their ability to induce directed chemotaxis in nearby responsive cells. All chemokines possess a number of conserved cysteine residues involved in intramolecular disulfide bond formation. Some chemokines are considered pro-inflammatory and can be induced during an immune response to recruit cells of the immune system to a site of infection, while others are considered homeostatic and are involved in controlling the migration of cells during normal processes of tissue maintenance or development. Chemokines are found in all vertebrates, some viruses and some bacteria.

label.value: structural constituent of chitin-based larval cuticle

definition.value: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of the chitin-based cuticle of a larva. An example of this is found in Drosophila melanogaster.

label.value: structural constituent of pupal chitin-based cuticle

definition.value: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of the chitin-based cuticle of a pupa. An example of this is found in Drosophila melanogaster.

label.value: structural constituent of adult chitin-based cuticle

definition.value: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of the chitin-based cuticle of an adult organism. An example of this is found in Drosophila melanogaster.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the beta subunit of the catenin complex.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with microtubules, filaments composed of tubulin monomers.

Combining with incidental electromagnetic radiation, particularly visible light, and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein -  promotes the exchange of GDP for GTP on the alpha subunit of a heterotrimeric G-protein complex.

A secretory organelle, some 50 nm in diameter, of presynaptic nerve terminals -  accumulates in high concentrations of neurotransmitters and secretes these into the synaptic cleft by fusion with the 'active zone' of the presynaptic plasma membrane.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a protein C-terminus, the end of any peptide chain at which the 1-carboxy function of a constituent amino acid is not attached in peptide linkage to another amino-acid residue.

Any protein complex that interacts with RNA polymerase II to increase (positive transcription elongation factor) or reduce (negative transcription elongation factor) the rate of transcription elongation.

label.value: positive transcription elongation factor complex b

definition.value: A transcription elongation factor complex that facilitates the transition from abortive to productive elongation by phosphorylating the CTD domain of the large subunit of DNA-directed RNA polymerase II, holoenzyme. Contains cyclin T and a cyclin-dependent protein kinase catalytic subunit.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate, to drive the unwinding of a DNA or RNA helix.
Catalysis of the transfer of monocarboxylic acids from one side of the membrane to the other. A monocarboxylic acid is an organic acid with one COOH group.
Combining with a pentraxin and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with a neuronal pentraxin and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
The action characteristic of eclosion hormone, a peptide hormone that, upon receptor binding, triggers the death of certain muscles and neurons during insect metamorphosis.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with high-density lipoprotein particle, a lipoprotein particle with a high density (typically 1.063-1.21 g|ml) and a diameter of 5-10 nm that contains APOAs and may contain APOCs and APOE.
Combining with a diuretic hormone and transmitting the signal to initiate a change in cell activity.
A ferritin complex located in the cell. Intracellular ferritin complexes contain 24 subunits, in a mixture of L (light) chains and H (heavy) chains.
Combining with an extracellular messenger and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to results in a change in cellular activity involved in axon guidance.
Increases the activity of an enzyme.

label.value: calcium sensitive guanylate cyclase activator activity

definition.value: Increases the activity of guanylate cyclase in response to a change in calcium ion concentration.
Increases the rate of GTP hydrolysis by the GTPase ARF.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with chitin, a linear polysaccharide consisting of beta-(1--gt-4)-linked N-acetyl-D-glucosamine residues.
Combining with glutamate and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Catalysis of the transmembrane transfer of a chloride ion by a channel that opens when extracellular glutamate has been bound by the channel complex or one of its constituent parts.
